rows, cols = 1,Well_Ed.shape[1]
fig,ax = plt.subplots(nrows=rows, ncols=cols, figsize=(30,10), sharey=True)
mnemonics = Well_Ed.columns
for i in range(cols):
    if i < cols-2:
        ax[i].plot(Well_Ed.iloc[:,i], Well_Ed.iloc[:,0],linewidth='1')
        ax[i].set_ylim(max(Well_Ed.iloc[:, 0]), min(Well_Ed.iloc[:, 0]))
        ax[i].minorticks_on()
        ax[i].grid(which='major', linestyle='-', linewidth='0.5', color='green')
        ax[i].grid(which='minor', linestyle=':', linewidth='0.5', color='black') #this is a comment
        ax[i].set_title('%s' %mnemonics[i], rotation = 30)
    elif i >= cols-2:
        F = np.vstack((Well_Ed.FORCE_2020_LITHOFACIES_LITHOLOGY,Well_Ed.FORCE_2020_LITHOFACIES_LITHOLOGY)).T
        ax[i].imshow(F, aspect='auto', cmap = 'gist_rainbow',extent=[0,1,max(Well_Ed.iloc[:, 0]), min(Well_Ed.iloc[:, 0])])
        ax[i].set_title('%s' % mnemonics[i], rotation = 30)
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0)
plt.show();

# Scaling the dataset
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
XScaled = scaler.fit_transform(Xdata)

# Train-Test Split the scaled dataset
X2_train, X2_test, y2_train, y2_test = train_test_split(XScaled, ydata, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
print("the size of the X2_train now is : ",X2_train.shape)
print("the size of the X2_test now is : ",X2_test.shape)

the size of the X2_train now is :  (9674, 9)
the size of the X2_test now is :  (2419, 9)
In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
DT = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42).fit(X2_train, y2_train)
In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix

train_preds = DT.predict(X2_train)
Training_Score  = accuracy_score(y2_train, train_preds)
print("The training accuracy_score is : {} % ".format(Training_Score*100))
Scoring = DT.score(X2_test, y2_test)

HyperParameter Tunning¶

Max_Depth¶

Max Depth: is the number of layer that decision tree can generate while learning from the training samples. limiting the maximum depth of the decision tree prevents the tree from overfitting all training samples and leads to better generalization

In [ ]:
def max_depth_error(md):
  model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=md, random_state=42)
  model.fit(X2_train, y2_train)
  train_acc = 1 - model.score(X2_train, y2_train)
  val_acc = 1 - model.score(X2_test, y2_test)
  return {'Max Depth': md, 'Training Error': train_acc, 'Test Error': val_acc}

max_leaf_nodes¶

to control the size of complexity of a decision tree is to limit the number of leaf nodes. This allows branches of the tree to have varying depths.

In [ ]:
def max_leaf_nodes_error(mln):
  model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_leaf_nodes=mln, random_state=42)
  model.fit(X2_train, y2_train)
  train_acc = 1 - model.score(X2_train, y2_train)
  test_acc = 1 - model.score(X2_test, y2_test)
  return {'max_leaf_nodes': mln, 'Training Error': train_acc, 'Test Error': test_acc}

# Creat General Function to test the parameters:
# check python **Kwargs: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/args-kwargs-python/#:~:text=The%20special%20syntax%20**kwargs,and%20any%20number%20of%20them).

def test_params(**params): 
  model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, n_jobs=-1, **params).fit(X2_train, y2_train)
  return model.score(X2_train, y2_train), model.score(X2_test, y2_test)
